Alexei Miller of Gazprom designates pipeline in Bulgaria as a start of a new gas era
The building start of the South-Stream-pipeline in Bulgaria represents the start one of the largest European energy projects, explained the Gazprom board of directors.
"The current event is a milestone: The structural work at the Bulgarian section of the South-Stream-gas pipeline, the largest and most important project in Europe, began", said the chairman of the board of Gazprom, Alexei Miller, on Thursday in an explanation.
The project is a key element for the energy security of the entire European continent.
South Stream should provide for more variety in Russia export route through Europe.
A contract dispute between Gazprom and its counterparts in the Ukraine, in which the large part of the Russian gas is stored for Europe, provide for an increased risk in regards to conventional routes how by official side to hear is.
Miller said, that would mean direct connection to Bulgaria, a member of the European Union,, that the risks connected geopolitical with transit countries would be turned off "for always".
Bulgarian consumers receive gas of South Stream to improved tariffs if the entire project 2015 goes in operation.
According to Gazprom, the structural work in other subordinate countries should begin on the planned route to the end of the year.
The pipeline is designed for an annual capacity of 62.3 billion cubic meters natural gas.
